One-Class Classification

Jimmy Azar

Here I demonstrate the one-class support vector machine. Two datasets are used for testing the classifier: (i) an artificial 2D dataset consisting for two Gaussian blobs at a distance from each other, forming the target class and (ii) a dataset consisting of boomerange-shaped branches.

The classifier requires setting the parameters nu \(\in [0,1]\) and gamma. For one-class SVM which is a boundary-based classifier, there is no parameter fracrej which represents the fraction of training objects to reject.

One-Class Support Vector Classifier

This classifier attempts to fit the target data within a hypersphere, while outliers fall outside. Slack variables are introduced to soften these constraints. A hypersphere is a rigid model, but with the use of a radial basis function (RBF) kernel, the hypersphere in kernel space may correspond to very flexible, complex boundaries in the original feature space. The support vector classifier formulates the problem as a convex optimization problem specified using Lagrange multipliers and solved numerically by quadratic programming. For a given test object, the classifier measures the distance to the center, \(a\) of the hypersphere and compares it to the radius, \(R\), to obtain a label.

\[Label(z) = \begin{cases} target, & \text{if } dist(z,a) < R \\ outlier, & \text{if } dist(z,a)) \geq R \\ \end{cases} \]

More, specifically, an object \(z\) is classified as belonging to the target class if and only if:

\[||z-a||^2 = (z \cdot z) - 2 \sum_i \alpha_i (z \cdot x_i) + \sum_{i,j} \alpha_i \alpha_j x_i \cdot x_j \leq R^2\] where \(R^2 = (x_k \cdot x_k) - 2 \sum_i \alpha_i (x_k \cdot x_i) + \sum_{i,j} \alpha_i \alpha_j x_i \cdot x_j\) represents the (square) distance from \(a\) to a support vector \(x_k\), thus lying at the boundary. The \(\alpha\)s are the Lagrange multipliers.

If we suppose a mapping \(\phi()\) for which the data \(\phi(x)\) becomes boundable within a hypersphere, then the above condition becomes:

\[ \phi(z) \cdot \phi(z) - 2 \sum_i \alpha_i \phi(z) \cdot \phi(x_i) + \sum_{i,j} \alpha_i \alpha_j \phi(x_i) \cdot \phi(x_j) \leq R^2\] The mapping \(\phi(x)\) does not need to be defined explicitly; instead using the kernel trick, we replace all inner products by the kernel function:

\[ K(z,z) - 2 \sum_i \alpha_i K(z,x_i) + \sum_{i,j} \alpha_i \alpha_j K(x_i,x_j) \leq R^2\] If the above condition is satisfied, then object \(z\) belongs to the taget class, else to the outlier class.

Dataset Generation

As a toy dataset, I generate two circularly symmetric Gaussian distributions in 2D with zero mean and with the identity matrix as covariance matrix. The training set consists only of inliers. The test set may contain inliers and outliers. I have drawn the outliers randomly from a uniform distribution. Inliers are assumed to have a 0 label while outliers have a 1 label.

gausscirc <- function(ntrn_inlier=100, ntst_inlier=20, ntst_outlier=20, show=TRUE, seed=1){
#Generates two circularly symmetric Gaussian distributions in 2D with zero mean and with the identity matrix as covariance matrix. 
#The training set consists only of inliers; their number is ntrn_inliers objects per distribution.
#The test set may consists of inliers (ntst_inlier objects per distribution) and should consist of outliers (ntst_outlier objects per distribution) drawn randomly from a uniform distribution.
#Inliers are assumed to have a '0' label while outliers have a '1' label. 
  
  if (!require("MASS")) install.packages("MASS") 
  library("MASS")

  #generate training inliers
  set.seed(seed)
  x <- 0.3*mvrnorm(ntrn_inlier, mu = c(0,0), Sigma = matrix(c(1,0,0,1),nrow = 2))
  xin <- rbind(x+2,x-2)
  xin <- cbind(xin,rep(0,ntrn_inlier)) #add '0' labels for inliers
  
  #generate test inliers (if any)
  if (ntst_inlier!=0){
    set.seed(seed+1)
    z <- 0.3*mvrnorm(ntst_inlier, mu = c(0,0), Sigma = matrix(c(1,0,0,1),nrow = 2))
    zin <- rbind(z+2,z-2)
    zin <- cbind(zin,rep(0,ntst_inlier)) #add '0' labels for inliers
  }
  else{zin <- numeric(0)}
  
  #generate test outliers from uniform distribution between [-5,5]
  set.seed(seed)
  f1 <- runif(ntst_outlier, min = -5, max = 5) #uniform distribution for feature 1
  set.seed(seed+1)
  f2 <- runif(ntst_outlier, min = -5, max = 5) #uniform distribution for feature 2
  zout <- cbind(f1,f2,rep(1,ntst_outlier)) 
  
  xtrn <- as.data.frame(xin)
  colnames(xtrn) <- c("f1","f2","label")

  xtst <- as.data.frame(rbind(zin,zout)) 
  colnames(xtst) <- c("f1","f2","label")

  if(show){
    plot(xin, col="blue", pch=20, xlab = "feature 1", ylab = "feature 2",
         xlim = c(-5.2,5.2), ylim = c(-5.2,5.2))
    points(zin,pch=20,col="violetred")
    points(zout,pch=17,col="violetred")
    legend("bottomright",legend = c("training inlier","test inlier","test outlier"),
           col = c("blue","violetred","violetred"), pch = c(20,20,17), cex=0.8)
  }
  
  l = list(xtrn,xtst) #create list of outputs
  return(l)
}

A second 2D artificial dataset is used which consists of two boomerang-shaped branches. The training set consists only of inliers. The test set may contain inliers and outliers. I have drawn the outliers randomly from a uniform distribution. Inliers are assumed to have a 0 label while outliers have a 1 label.

boomerang <- function(Ntrn=c(50,50), Ntst = c(20,20), ntst_outlier=100, s=1, 
                      show=TRUE,seed=1){
  #Generate a boomerang-shaped training set with the number of objects in each branch described by Ntrn.
  #The number on test set inliers in each branch is given by Ntst.
  #The number of test set outliers is ntst_outlier drawn randomly from a uniform distribution. 
  #Parameter s controls the width of the branches.
  
  if (!require("MASS")) install.packages("MASS") 
  library("MASS")
  
  r <- 5  #size of boomerang
  
  #generate training inliers
  set.seed(seed)
  domaina = 0.125*pi + runif(n = Ntrn[1], min = 0, max =1) * 1.25*pi
  t1 <- mvrnorm(n=Ntrn[1], mu = c(0,0), Sigma = matrix(c(1,0,0,1),nrow = 2))*s 
  a <- cbind(r*sin(domaina),r*cos(domaina)) + t1
  
  domainb = 0.375*pi - runif(n = Ntrn[2], min = 0, max = 1) * 1.25*pi
  t2 <- mvrnorm(n = Ntrn[2], mu = c(0,0), Sigma = matrix(c(1,0,0,1),nrow = 2))*s 
  b <-  cbind(r*sin(domainb),r*cos(domainb)) + t2 +
              matrix(c(-0.75*r,-0.75*r),nrow=Ntrn[2],ncol=2)
  
  #combine the two branches into a training set
  xin <- rbind(a,b)
  xin <- cbind(xin,rep(0,nrow(xin)))
  xtrn <- as.data.frame(xin)
  colnames(xtrn) <- c("f1","f2","label") 
  
  #get boundary limits
  mn <- apply(xtrn[,1:2],2,min)
  mx <- apply(xtrn[,1:2],2,max)
  xmin <- mn[1]; ymin <- mn[2]
  xmax <- mx[1]; ymax <- mx[2]
  low <- min(xmin,ymin)-1 #add margin
  high <- max(xmax,ymax)+1 #add margin
  
  #generate test inliers (if any)
  if (sum(Ntst)!=0){
    set.seed(seed+1)
    domaina = 0.125*pi + runif(n = Ntst[1], min = 0, max =1) * 1.25*pi
    t1 <- mvrnorm(n=Ntst[1], mu = c(0,0), Sigma = matrix(c(1,0,0,1),nrow = 2))*s 
    a <- cbind(r*sin(domaina),r*cos(domaina)) + t1
    
    domainb = 0.375*pi - runif(n = Ntst[2], min = 0, max = 1) * 1.25*pi
    t2 <- mvrnorm(n = Ntst[2], mu = c(0,0), Sigma = matrix(c(1,0,0,1),nrow = 2))*s 
    b <- cbind(r*sin(domainb),r*cos(domainb)) + t2 + 
         matrix(c(-0.75*r,-0.75*r),nrow=Ntst[2],ncol=2)
    
    zin <- rbind(a,b)
    zin <- cbind(zin,rep(0,nrow(zin))) #add labels '0'
  }
  else{zin <- numeric(0)}
  
  #generate test outliers from uniform distribution
  set.seed(seed+2)
  f1 <- runif(ntst_outlier, min = low, max = high) #uniform distribution for feature 1
  set.seed(seed+3)
  f2 <- runif(ntst_outlier, min = low, max = high) #uniform distribution for feature 2
  zout <- cbind(f1,f2,rep(1,ntst_outlier)) #add labels '1'
  
  #combine into a test set
  xtst <- as.data.frame(rbind(zin,zout)) 
  colnames(xtst) <- c("f1","f2","label")
  
  if(show){
    plot(xin,col="blue",pch=20,xlab = "feature 1", ylab = "feature 2",
         xlim = c(low,high), ylim = c(low,high))
    points(zin,pch=20,col="violetred") #add test set inliers
    points(zout,pch=17,col="violetred") #add test set outliers
    legend("bottomright",legend = c("training inlier","test inlier","test outlier"),
           col = c("blue","violetred","violetred"), pch = c(20,20,17), cex=0.8)
  }
  
  l = list(xtrn,xtst) #create list of outputs
  return(l)
}

Classifier

R already has the function svm() which can be used as a one-class support vector classifier. As input, the training set contains only examples of inliers (target objects). The type of kernel is set to radial (RBF), and the parameters nu and gamma have to be selected or optimized using grid search.

Visualization of decision boundary

For visualizing the decision boundary of the SVM OCC in 2D, I have written the below function vizSvm() which plots the training (inlier) objects, then calls the SVM classifier which is trained on these objects in order to classify a mesh grid of points covering the range of the training set in both x- and y- directions. Each grid point is classified as either outlier or inlier and is plotted in different color for each case. In addition, the boundary that separates inliers from outliers is plotted as a contour line in black.

vizSvm <- function(model, data, resolution = 100){
  #visualize decision boundary
  #data is labeled 2D dataset with labels as 3rd (last) column
  #grid resolution is 100 points per axis by default 

  cl <- data[,3]
  kk <- length(unique(cl))
  color <- c("blue","violetred")
  shape <- c(20,17) #dot, triangle
  
  #find x-, y- limits of data
  mn <- apply(data[,1:2],2,min)
  mx <- apply(data[,1:2],2,max)
  xmin <- mn[1]; ymin <- mn[2]
  xmax <- mx[1]; ymax <- mx[2]
  low <- min(xmin,ymin)-3 #add margin
  high <- max(xmax,ymax)+3 #add margin
  
  #plot data objects in blue
  plot(data[,1:2], col = color[1], pch = shape[as.integer(cl)+1L],
       xlim = c(low,high),ylim = c(low,high),xlab("Feature 1"),ylab("Feature 2"))
  
  #set-up grid
  xs <- seq(low, high, length.out = resolution)
  ys <- seq(low, high, length.out = resolution)
  g <- cbind(rep(xs, each=resolution), rep(ys, time = resolution))
  g <- as.data.frame(g)
  colnames(g) <- colnames(data[,1:2])
  
  L <- predict(model, g)
  if (class(L)=="logical") L <- (as.integer(!L)) #one-class SVM case
  else if (class(L)=="factor") L <- as.numeric(as.character(L)) #two-class SVM case   
  
  #plot grid points in colors reflecting their predicted labels
  points(g, col = color[as.integer(L)+1L], pch = ".")
  
  #add decision boundary contour
  z <- matrix(L+1L, nrow = resolution, byrow = TRUE)
  contour(xs, ys, z, add = TRUE, drawlabels = FALSE,
          lwd = 2, levels = (1:(kk-1))+.5)
}

Demo

In this demo, I use all the above functions to show the resulting output for two artificial datasets: the first consisting of two separate Gaussian blobs, and the second consisting of two boomerang-shaped branches.

First, I call gausscirc() to generate a dataset.

l <- gausscirc(ntrn_inlier = 200, ntst_inlier =  100, ntst_outlier = 100, 
               show = TRUE, seed=1)

xtrn <- l[[1]]
xtst <- l[[2]]

I split the original test set into a validation set (for tuning the hyperparameter fracrej) and a final test set for assessing the performance of the classifier. The split I have selected is a random 50%-50% stratified split.

#Split test set into validation set and final test set.
inliers <- which(xtst[,ncol(xtst)]==0)
outliers <- which(xtst[,ncol(xtst)]==1)
ind_in <- sample(inliers,floor(0.5*length(inliers))) #50% stratified split
ind_out <- sample(outliers,floor(0.5*length(outliers))) 
xval <- xtst[c(ind_in,ind_out),]
xtst <- xtst[-c(ind_in,ind_out),]

Using an RBF kernel, and for a range of values of gamma = \((2^{-15},2^{-13},...,2^{3})\) and nu = \(0.05,0.1,...,0.95\) (\(\in [0,1]\)), select the optimal values which minimize the following false-rate error defined as: \(\sqrt{FPR^2+FNR^2}\), where \(FPR\) is the false positive rate and \(FNR\) is the false negative rate, i.e. \(FPR = FP/(FP+TN)\) and \(FNR = FN/(FN+TP)\). Minimizing this false-error rate is equivalent to obtaining a point closest to the upper left corner of an ROC curve where \(1-FPR\) (sensitivity; target accepted) is plotted against \(FNR\) (1-specificity; outliers accepted). Note that in this context, I consider outliers as positively labeled with 1, while inliers are negatively labeled as 0.

if (!require("e1071")) install.packages("e1071") 
if (!require("caret")) install.packages("caret") 
library(e1071)
library(caret)

#Optimize hyperparameters
steps <- seq(from = -15, to = 3, by = 2)
gamma <- 2^steps #range of values for gamma
nu <- seq(from = 0.05, to = 0.95, by = 0.05) #range of values for nu
error <- matrix(NA,nrow=length(gamma),ncol = length(nu))

for (i in seq_along(gamma)){
  for (j in seq_along(nu)){
    model <- svm(label ~ f1 + f2, data = xtrn, type="one-classification",
                 nu=nu[j],kernel="radial",gamma = gamma[i])
    pred <- predict(model, xval[,1:2]) #create predictions
    cf <- confusionMatrix(factor(as.numeric(!pred),levels=c(0,1)),factor(xval[,3],levels=c(0,1)))
    t <- cf$table
    TN <- t[1]; TP <- t[4]
    FN <- t[3]; FP <- t[2]
    FPR <- FP/(FP+TN)
    FNR <- FN/(FN+TP)
    if(is.nan(FPR)) FPR = 0
    if(is.nan(FNR)) FNR = 0
    error[i,j] <- sqrt(FPR^2 + FNR^2)  #false-rate error (i.e. distance to ROC upper left corner) 
    #error[i,j] <- (FPR+FNR)/2   #balanced error
  }
}

loc <- which(error == min(error), arr.ind = TRUE)
g <- gamma[loc[1]]
n <- nu[loc[2]]

Run the model with the optimal parameters selected.

#model using optimal parameters
model <- svm(label ~ f1 + f2, data = xtrn, type="one-classification",
             nu=n,kernel="radial",gamma = g)
print(model)
## 
## Call:
## svm(formula = label ~ f1 + f2, data = xtrn, type = "one-classification", 
##     nu = n, kernel = "radial", gamma = g)
## 
## 
## Parameters:
##    SVM-Type:  one-classification 
##  SVM-Kernel:  radial 
##       gamma:  0.5 
##          nu:  0.05 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors:  22

Test the optimized model using the test set

#Test the model on test set
pred <- predict(model, xtst[,1:2]) #create predictions on test set
cf <- confusionMatrix(factor(as.numeric(!pred),levels=c(0,1)),
                      factor(xtst[,3],levels=c(0,1)))
print(cf)

##                                           
##                   Kappa : 0.8657

Generate probabilistic-output from the scores returned by the model. Consider the largest positive score as the distance or radius from the innermost inlier to the boundary. Such a score should be mapped to a probability of 1, whereas a score of 0 should map to a probability of 1/2 (i.e.the object lies on the boundary). Large negative scores tending to \(-\infty\) would correspond to a probability of 0. To represent this, scores ranging from \([-\infty,R]\) are mapped by an exponential function that passes through the points \((0,1/2)\) and \((R,1)\).

#probabilistic output
out <- predict(model,xtst[,1:2], decision.values = TRUE) #positive distances = inliers, negative distances = outliers
out <- attr(out,"decision.values")
R <- max(out) #largest inlier distance to boundary, which is necessarily closed (hypershere in kernel space)
p <- exp(log(2)/R*(out-R))   #exp. function over [-\infty,R], passing (0,1/2) and (R,1)

Finally, visualize the training set and decision boundary of the classifier. Also add the test set objects with different markers for inliers and outliers.

#visualize decision boundary and training set
vizSvm(model, data = xtrn, resolution = 100)

#add final test objects (inliers and outliers)
shape <- c(20,17) #dot, triangle
points(xtst[,1:2],col="violetred",pch=shape[xtst[,3]+1]) #add test objects
legend("bottomright",legend = c("training inlier","test inlier","test outlier"), 
       col = c("blue","violetred","violetred"), pch = c(20,20,17), cex=0.8)
